Unified Multimodal Voice Intelligence System (UMVIS v2.1)

A Latent Dynamical Framework for Bidirectional Speech-Text Transformation with Decoupled Content, Prosody, and Speaker Dynamics

Author: ouadi Maakoul 

---

Abstract

Contemporary conversational AI systems rely on a fragmented cascade of independent models for Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR), Large Language Model inference, and Text-to-Speech (TTS) synthesis. This pipeline architecture introduces cumulative latency exceeding 500ms, results in catastrophic information loss of prosodic and paralinguistic features, and suffers from fundamental modality representation mismatch. This work proposes the Unified Multimodal Voice Intelligence System (UMVIS), a conceptual design for a single, end-to-end neural framework that models speech and text as dual observable projections of an evolving Latent Dynamical Voice System (LDVS). UMVIS is designed to eliminate the intermediate text bottleneck entirely by employing a hybrid tokenization strategy—utilizing continuous acoustic embeddings for high-fidelity input encoding while predicting discrete neural codec tokens for efficient autoregressive generation. The core architectural innovation is a decoupled latent dynamical system \mathbf{Z}(t) = [\mathbf{Z}_c(t); \mathbf{Z}_p(t); \mathbf{Z}_s(t); \mathbf{Z}_\epsilon(t)] that evolves over time via a Structured State-Space Model (SSM) with explicit mechanisms for conversational phase transitions (Latent State Reset), long-form temporal anchoring (Differentiable Anchor Mechanism), and predictive latency hiding. We provide rigorous probabilistic foundations grounded in variational inference with a multimodal VAMPrior for prosodic expressivity, derive a multi-objective training strategy incorporating differentiable temporal alignment (Soft-DTW), cross-modal contrastive learning (InfoNCE), and Conditional Mutual Information (CMI) constraints for robust yet context-aware disentanglement, and outline a comprehensive data generation pipeline to address the critical scarcity of temporally aligned speech-text-prosody triples. Theoretical analysis indicates that a UMVIS implementation would be capable of achieving proactive (near-zero) perceived latency through predictive generation, establishing a new paradigm for real-time, emotionally intelligent, and controllable spoken dialogue systems.

Keywords: Unified Speech-Text Modeling, Latent Dynamical Systems, Prosody Generation, Multimodal Transformers, State-Space Models, Disentangled Representation Learning, Real-Time Speech Synthesis, Contrastive Learning, Conceptual Architecture

