2. Related Work

UMVIS builds upon and extends several active research directions. We position our contributions relative to the state of the art, with particular attention to clarifying the distinctions between UMVIS and prior unified modeling efforts.

2.1 Unified Speech-Text Models

The evolution toward unified voice models has accelerated significantly in recent years. AudioPaLM (Rubenstein et al., 2023) pioneered the use of a decoder-only transformer operating on discrete audio tokens generated by SoundStream, demonstrating that a single model can perform both speech recognition and synthesis. However, subsequent analysis revealed significant DRI issues arising from the quantization step, motivating the development of hybrid approaches.

Several concurrent research directions have explored variations on unified architectures. Approaches leveraging flow matching for prosody control have shown promise in generating expressive speech from text, while other work has investigated late fusion and multi-level fission to amplify cross-modal transfer. Recent omnimodal models such as Qwen3.5-Omni (Alibaba, March 2026) and Nemotron 3 VoiceChat (NVIDIA, April 2026) have pushed the boundaries of real-time multimodal interaction, integrating ASR, LLM, and TTS into cohesive systems. However, these systems remain fundamentally cascaded in their internal representation or rely on monolithic transformer architectures that do not explicitly model temporal dynamics.

Differentiation: Unlike these models, which treat latent representations as static vectors and lack explicit turn-taking awareness, UMVIS models temporal evolution through an SSM core with explicit phase transition mechanisms. Critically, UMVIS incorporates a Latent State Reset (LSR) at conversational boundaries—a feature absent from all prior unified architectures. This prevents the model from carrying over the user's acoustic environment or prosodic patterns into its own generated speech, addressing a fundamental limitation of continuous-state systems deployed in conversational settings.

2.2 Dynamical Systems for Prosody and Speech Modeling

Recent work has explored dynamical and causal approaches to prosody generation. The structural causal model proposed by Causal Prosody Mediation for TTS (2026) formulates a directed acyclic graph of how text, emotion, and speaker identity jointly influence prosodic features, enabling fine-grained control over expressiveness. Mamba (Gu and Dao, 2023) and its derivatives offer linear-time sequence modeling through selective state-space mechanisms, retaining content selection capabilities while achieving five times higher inference throughput than comparably sized Transformers.

Differentiation: UMVIS integrates SSM-based latent dynamics with explicit factorization across content, prosody, speaker, and interaction subspaces. Crucially, we add a contractive mapping constraint (\|\bar{\mathbf{A}}(t)\|_2 \leq 1 - \delta) to ensure numerical stability during continuous streaming operation—a guarantee not provided by standard Mamba implementations. Furthermore, we introduce the novel concept of latent state resets at conversational boundaries, which has no direct precedent in the SSM or dynamical speech modeling literature.

2.3 Disentangled Representation Learning in Speech

Disentanglement is a core challenge in speech representation learning. Prior work has employed sequential disentanglement to separate speaker identity, linguistic content, and emotional representation from acoustic signals. The CLUB estimator (Cheng et al., 2020) provides a tractable upper bound on mutual information, enabling efficient MI minimization in high-dimensional latent spaces. However, unconditional MI minimization can inadvertently remove legitimate dependencies—for instance, a speaker's identity influences their typical pitch range and prosodic tendencies, which should be preserved for natural-sounding synthesis.

Differentiation: UMVIS introduces Conditional Mutual Information (CMI) constraints, I(\mathbf{Z}_p; \mathbf{Z}_s \mid \mathbf{Z}_c), which preserve natural speaker-dependent prosodic patterns while preventing inappropriate identity leakage. This refinement is critical for producing speech that is both expressive and faithful to the target speaker's characteristics. We also enforce orthogonality among primary factors through cosine similarity penalties, ensuring cleaner separation than approaches relying solely on information-theoretic objectives.

2.4 Differentiable Temporal Alignment

Soft-DTW (Cuturi and Blondel, 2017) enables end-to-end training via backpropagation through time series comparisons, with quadratic time and space complexity. This differentiable alignment has been successfully applied in TTS systems to synchronize acoustic and linguistic representations during training. More recent work has explored optimal transport formulations for alignment in multimodal settings.

Differentiation: UMVIS augments global Soft-DTW with a Differentiable Anchor Mechanism that enforces synchronization at phoneme boundaries. While phoneme anchors have been used in voice conversion for speaker-content separation (e.g., SABR), UMVIS applies this concept to real-time streaming stabilization of an SSM. The anchor mechanism prevents the gradual drift between content and prosody trajectories that plagues streaming SSM-based generation, ensuring long-form coherence.

2.5 Streaming and Low-Latency Speech Synthesis

Significant progress has been made in reducing the initial latency of streaming TTS systems. VoXtream (2025) achieves first-packet latency of 102ms on GPU, representing the current state of the art for reactive TTS latency. Block-wise guided attention masks and incremental decoding strategies have been widely adopted to enable streaming operation.

Differentiation: UMVIS goes beyond reactive latency reduction by introducing Predictive Latency Hiding. Rather than waiting for the user to finish speaking before beginning generation, the model anticipates and pre-computes the likely response trajectory during the listening phase. This transforms the 120ms reactive latency into near-zero perceived delay—a qualitative shift in conversational fluidity that has not been demonstrated in prior work. The predictive mechanism operates directly on the unified latent space \mathbf{Z}(t), enabling more accurate anticipation than token-based speculation approaches.

