6. Proposed Data Generation and Training Pipeline

6.1 The Data Alignment Challenge

Obtaining perfectly aligned speech-text-prosody triples at scale remains a critical challenge. We propose a multi-stage pipeline combining existing corpora, forced alignment, and synthetic augmentation.

6.2 Base Dataset Aggregation

The following publicly available datasets are aggregated:

· LibriTTS: 585 hours of read English speech from audiobooks, with multiple speakers.
· VCTK: 44 hours of read speech from 109 speakers with diverse accents.
· EmoV-DB: 7 hours of emotional speech (5 emotions) from 4 speakers.
· Common Voice: Large-scale crowd-sourced speech in multiple languages.
· LJSpeech: 24 hours of single-speaker expressive speech.
· ESD (Emotional Speech Database): 10 speakers × 5 emotions.

6.3 Forced Alignment and Prosody Extraction

· Montreal Forced Aligner (MFA): Phoneme-level alignments for all English corpora.
· CREPE: Pitch (F_0) extraction at 10ms resolution.
· RMS Energy: Frame-level energy computation.
· Spectral Tilt: Extracted via linear predictive coding analysis.

6.4 Synthetic Data Augmentation

To address the scarcity of emotionally varied prosody, we propose:

1. Contrastive Data Generation: Using a pretrained TTS model to generate the same text with varied prosodic controls (happy, sad, questioning, urgent), creating paired examples for contrastive learning.
2. SpeechWeave-Style Augmentation: Multilingual TTS expansion to improve cross-lingual prosodic generalization.
3. Prosodic Perturbation: Applying controlled pitch shifting, time stretching, and energy scaling to existing samples.

6.5 Self-Supervised Pretraining

Before full end-to-end training, we propose a Masked Prosody Model (MPM) pretraining phase:

· Mask random segments of the acoustic sequence (100–300ms spans).
· Reconstruct the masked prosodic features (F_0, energy) from context.
· This learns robust acoustic and prosodic representations without requiring aligned text.

