7. Theoretical Latency Analysis with Predictive Hiding

7.1 Reactive vs. Predictive Latency

Traditional streaming TTS systems exhibit reactive latency: the delay between receiving the final text token and producing the first audio sample. VoXtream (2025) demonstrates this can be reduced to approximately 102ms for the TTS component alone. However, in a cascaded pipeline, additional latency accumulates from ASR (200–400ms for streaming recognition) and LLM inference (100–300ms for token generation), yielding total pipeline latency of 400–800ms—well above the 200ms threshold for natural conversation.

7.2 Predictive Latency Hiding in UMVIS

UMVIS transforms this reactive latency through anticipatory pre-computation. The perceived latency model is:

\Delta_{\text{perceived}} = \max(0, \Delta_{\text{reactive}} - \tau_{\text{predict}} - \tau_{\text{turn-gap}})

where:

· \Delta_{\text{reactive}} \approx 120\text{ms} (UMVIS TTS decoder latency)
· \tau_{\text{predict}} \approx 300\text{ms} (prediction lead time while user is still speaking)
· \tau_{\text{turn-gap}} \approx 200\text{ms} (natural pause between turns)

For typical conversation, \Delta_{\text{perceived}} = \max(0, 120 - 300 - 200) = 0\text{ms}. The system responds as if it had zero latency—a qualitative shift in user experience.

7.3 Real-Time Factor (RTF) Analysis

The RTF is defined as:

\text{RTF} = \frac{\text{Computation Time}}{\text{Audio Duration}}

For UMVIS, we estimate the per-frame computational cost based on a 1.5B parameter configuration:

Component FLOPs per Frame Notes
Speech Encoder 0.8 GFLOPs Conv stem + projection
LDVS Core (SSM) 2.1 GFLOPs 10 layers, d=1024
Cross-Attention 0.9 GFLOPs 8 heads, sparse attention
Text Decoder 0.3 GFLOPs CTC, beam size 1
Speech Decoder 1.8 GFLOPs Codec + flow matching (4 steps)
Total 5.9 GFLOPs/frame Frame rate = 50Hz

Total FLOPs per second of audio: 5.9 \times 50 = 295 GFLOPs/s.

An NVIDIA H100 GPU provides approximately 1000 TFLOPs/s (FP16/BF16 with Tensor Cores). Assuming 40% utilization (typical for autoregressive decoding), the available throughput is 400 TFLOPs/s. The RTF is therefore:

\text{RTF} = \frac{295 \times 10^9}{400 \times 10^{12}} \approx 0.31

This places UMVIS well within the real-time envelope (< 1.0), with substantial headroom for larger batch sizes or additional features. The estimate is conservative; further optimizations (kernel fusion, quantization) would reduce RTF below 0.2.

7.4 Contractive Stability Guarantee

The contractive constraint \|\bar{\mathbf{A}}(t)\|_2 \leq 1 - \delta ensures that even in extended 24/7 operation without resets, the latent state remains bounded. This prevents the numerical drift and state explosion that can affect standard SSM implementations during prolonged streaming inference.

