Appendix C: Derivation of Conditional CLUB Estimator

C.1 Original CLUB Estimator

Cheng et al. (2020) proposed the Contrastive Log-ratio Upper Bound (CLUB) for mutual information. For unconditional MI I(X; Y), the CLUB estimator is:

I_{\text{CLUB}}(X; Y) = \mathbb{E}_{p(x,y)}[\log q_\psi(y \mid x)] - \mathbb{E}_{p(x)p(y)}[\log q_\psi(y \mid x)]

where q_\psi(y \mid x) is a variational approximation to the conditional distribution p(y \mid x). It can be shown that I_{\text{CLUB}}(X; Y) \geq I(X; Y) when q_\psi is sufficiently expressive.

Proof of Upper Bound Property:

I(X; Y) = \mathbb{E}_{p(x,y)}\left[\log \frac{p(y \mid x)}{p(y)}\right] = \mathbb{E}_{p(x,y)}[\log p(y \mid x)] - \mathbb{E}_{p(y)}[\log p(y)]

Since we do not have access to the true p(y \mid x), we substitute the variational approximation q_\psi:

I_{\text{v}}(X; Y) = \mathbb{E}_{p(x,y)}[\log q_\psi(y \mid x)] - \mathbb{E}_{p(x)p(y)}[\log q_\psi(y \mid x)]

The gap between I_{\text{v}} and true I is:

I_{\text{v}} - I = \mathbb{E}_{p(x)}[D_{\text{KL}}(p(y \mid x) \parallel q_\psi(y \mid x))] \geq 0

Thus I_{\text{v}} is an upper bound.

C.2 Extension to Conditional Mutual Information

We seek an estimator for I(X; Y \mid Z). By definition:

I(X; Y \mid Z) = \mathbb{E}_{p(z)}[I(X; Y \mid Z=z)] = \mathbb{E}_{p(z)}\left[ \mathbb{E}_{p(x,y \mid z)}\left[\log \frac{p(y \mid x, z)}{p(y \mid z)}\right] \right]

Introduce a variational approximation q_\psi(y \mid x, z) for p(y \mid x, z). The conditional CLUB estimator is:

I_{\text{CLUB}}(X; Y \mid Z) = \mathbb{E}_{p(x,y,z)}[\log q_\psi(y \mid x, z)] - \mathbb{E}_{p(z)p(x)p(y)}[\log q_\psi(y \mid x, z)]

where the second expectation is over the product of marginals p(z)p(x)p(y). Note that the true conditional distribution in the second term should be p(y \mid z), but we approximate it by sampling y from the marginal p(y) for simplicity and tractability; this is a standard approximation in CLUB implementations.

Gap Analysis:

I_{\text{CLUB}} - I = \mathbb{E}_{p(z)}\left[ \mathbb{E}_{p(x \mid z)}[D_{\text{KL}}(p(y \mid x, z) \parallel q_\psi(y \mid x, z))] \right] + \mathbb{E}_{p(z)}[D_{\text{KL}}(p(y \mid z) \parallel p(y))] \geq 0

The second term is an additional bias introduced by using the marginal p(y) instead of p(y \mid z). In practice, if Z is high-dimensional, this bias may be non-negligible. An alternative formulation that avoids this bias uses a second variational network r_\omega(y \mid z) to approximate p(y \mid z):

I_{\text{CLUB-cond}}(X; Y \mid Z) = \mathbb{E}_{p(x,y,z)}[\log q_\psi(y \mid x, z)] - \mathbb{E}_{p(x,z)p(y \mid z)}[\log q_\psi(y \mid x, z)]

This version provides a tighter bound but requires learning r_\omega(y \mid z). In UMVIS, we use the simpler formulation for computational efficiency, as the bias term is typically small relative to the MI values in our setting.

C.3 Implementation in UMVIS

In our context, X = \mathbf{Z}_p (prosody latent), Y = \mathbf{Z}_s (speaker latent), and Z = \mathbf{Z}_c (content latent). The variational network q_\psi(\mathbf{z}_s \mid \mathbf{z}_p, \mathbf{z}_c) is a 3-layer MLP that outputs the mean and log-variance of a Gaussian distribution over \mathbf{Z}_s. The conditional CLUB loss is:

\mathcal{L}_{\text{CMI}} = \frac{1}{B} \sum_{i=1}^B \log q_\psi(\mathbf{z}_s^{(i)} \mid \mathbf{z}_p^{(i)}, \mathbf{z}_c^{(i)}) - \frac{1}{B} \sum_{i=1}^B \log q_\psi(\tilde{\mathbf{z}}_s^{(i)} \mid \mathbf{z}_p^{(i)}, \mathbf{z}_c^{(i)})

where \tilde{\mathbf{z}}_s^{(i)} are shuffled speaker latents from the batch (breaking the pairing), approximating samples from the product of marginals.

