D.2 Orthogonal Projection Layer

The orthogonal projection layer ensures that the subspaces \mathcal{Z}_c, \mathcal{Z}_p, \mathcal{Z}_s remain mutually orthogonal. Given latent vectors \mathbf{z}_c, \mathbf{z}_p, \mathbf{z}_s, we maintain a set of learnable basis matrices \mathbf{U}_c \in \mathbb{R}^{d_z \times d_c}, \mathbf{U}_p \in \mathbb{R}^{d_z \times d_p}, \mathbf{U}_s \in \mathbb{R}^{d_z \times d_s} with orthonormal columns (enforced via a penalty on \|\mathbf{U}_i^T \mathbf{U}_i - \mathbf{I}\|_F^2).

The projection of a vector \mathbf{v} onto subspace i is \text{Proj}_i(\mathbf{v}) = \mathbf{U}_i \mathbf{U}_i^T \mathbf{v}. The orthogonalization step before cross-attention is:

```
def orthogonalize(z_c, z_p, z_s):
    # Remove projections onto other subspaces
    z_c_orth = z_c - U_p @ (U_p.T @ z_c) - U_s @ (U_s.T @ z_c)
    z_p_orth = z_p - U_c @ (U_c.T @ z_p) - U_s @ (U_s.T @ z_p)
    z_s_orth = z_s - U_c @ (U_c.T @ z_s) - U_p @ (U_p.T @ z_s)
    return z_c_orth, z_p_orth, z_s_orth
```

D.3 VAMPrior Implementation

The VAMPrior is implemented with K = 500 learnable pseudo-inputs \{\mathbf{u}^{(k)}\}_{k=1}^K in the data space (concatenated acoustic and text features). During training, the prior distribution is:

p(\mathbf{z}_p) = \frac{1}{K} \sum_{k=1}^K q_\phi(\mathbf{z}_p \mid \mathbf{u}^{(k)})

The pseudo-inputs are initialized to random training samples and optimized jointly with the model parameters. The KL divergence in the ELBO becomes:

D_{\text{KL}}(q_\phi(\mathbf{z}_p \mid \mathbf{x}, \mathbf{y}) \parallel p(\mathbf{z}_p)) = \mathbb{E}_{q_\phi}[\log q_\phi] - \mathbb{E}_{q_\phi}\left[\log \frac{1}{K}\sum_{k=1}^K q_\phi(\mathbf{z}_p \mid \mathbf{u}^{(k)})\right]

We use the reparameterization trick for gradient estimation.

